Fig. 6b displayed the (F/F0
) bar diagram in the presence of each metal ion (5 mM). The F and F0
 exhibit the PL intensities in the presence and absence of metal ions with the excitation of UV light (365 nm), respectively. Obviously, other metal ions only have slight effects on PL intensity of CQDs except for the Fe3+ (>90% decrease) and Cu2+ ions (∼30% decrease), implying most of metal ions can not cause any interference for Fe3+ detection. Compared to other metal ions, much stronger affinity and faster chelating process of Fe3+ with the oxygen (or nitrogen)-containing groups on the surface of the CQDs may be responsible for such a discrimination effect [53,54]. These results indicate the as-prepared CQDs possess high selectivity and stable response to detection of Fe3+ in aqueous solution.
